It looks like their engineers used `2^9` (`512`) bit to store a year:

`1.1.1970` (datekey: `33`) and `1.1.1971` (datekey: `545`) = `512`  
`1.1.1972` (datekey: `1569`) and `1.1.1972` (datekey: `2081`) = `512`

And `2^5` (`32`) bit to store a month.

So a modulo calculation could look like the following:

```
function getDate(dateKey) {
  const yearOffset = (dateKey - 32) % 512;
  const year = (dateKey - 32 - yearOffset) / 512;
  const day = yearOffset % 32;
  const month = (yearOffset - day) / 32;
  return new Date(year + 1970, month, day);
}
```

Does anyone know why they came up with such a logic?

